column2:
I'm running this locally on Windows 10 and do not have access to Gitter at work.  I have built everything but cannot get a collector working at all.  What I've done:

1) First I tried running just the api with  java -jar api.jar --spring.config.location="..\..\dashboard.properties" and the UI with gulp serve --local true.  I saw the dashboard but there was no data and I could not create any users.  I saw some earlier issues suggesting that the mock data model may be broken so I tried to configure a GitHub (Enterprise) collector.

2) I created application.properties for GitHub and tried to run the collector from the \target folder like this:
java -jar github-scm-collector-3.0.1.jar --spring.config.name=github --spring.config.location=c:\code\hygieia\collectors\scm\github\application.properties

I get an error: "Exception authenticating MongoCredential ... userName='dashboarduser', source='dashboarddb' ..."

I confirmed that MongoDB is running on the default port and that the dashboarddb and dashboarduser exist.  Password is just "test123" and is set as such in properties file.  Questions:

- what should I try next?
- once I fix this error, should I manually start the collector, api, UI in that order?  

Thanks!
column5: Unable to get started with a basic collector.
column11:
442619163 To clarify, when I ran with --local true what happened is that user creation failed.  It would just return me to the signup screen then on try #2 tell me the user existed.  I found issues where other people had this happen but didn't see an answer.  If I can get a real collector running I don't really care about the test data :-) freecellwiz
442619804 Are you getting the mongo error while running the GitHub collector? Sbrenthughes
443216625 Yes, the Mongo error is while running the collector.  I tried a few things and made some progress:

* When I run the GitHub collector I get "Exception authenticating MongoCredential{mechanism=SCRAM-SHA-1, userName='dashboarduser', source='dashboarddb', password=" 
* If I run the collector with the db user/pwd commented out in application.properties, it runs (no repo data is pulled yet but it's hitting GitHub - I can solve that part)
* I also commented out the db user/pwd in dashboard.properties for consistency, but now the login screen is missing the form.  

A bit later today (I'm at work) I may just trying deleting and creating the database in case I've gotten something in a bad state somehow.  I would like to understand the user/pwd issue.   freecellwiz
443218696 The login screen missing is likely a browser cache issue. Clear your browser cache or open in incognito mode. Are we good to close this? Sbrenthughes
443246191 Yes, thanks.  If I have other questions I'll use Gitter when I'm outside a corporate network. freecellwiz
442079505 Can you post your properties file? Sbrenthughes
442149455 Sure.  I'm probably missing something obvious.  
[application.properties.txt](https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/files/2621172/application.properties.txt)

 freecellwiz
442456639 Can you verify whether or not you are able to create a new user via the ui? Sbrenthughes
442610399 Hi Brent - 

Actually yes I can.  I was thrown earlier because when running --local true it didn't work.  If I run just the API in one command window and the UI in a second (just "gulp serve") I can create an admin user and get "Welcome ADMIN".  

Now I just need to get a collector working to get an idea of how the tool works and if it will help our teams.  It looks fantastic.  GitHub was just the one I picked as a test.  Our stack includes GitHub Enterprise/TeamCity/Artifactory/Jira.  I don't know if it matters that we use self-hosted GH and not github.com.

 freecellwiz
442611695 It does not matter. I just wanted to make sure it was setup from the ui/api side. Since this is local, can you comment out the db user and db password and re run the collector? Sbrenthughes
442619163 To clarify, when I ran with --local true what happened is that user creation failed.  It would just return me to the signup screen then on try #2 tell me the user existed.  I found issues where other people had this happen but didn't see an answer.  If I can get a real collector running I don't really care about the test data :-) freecellwiz

* When I run the GitHub collector I get "Exception authenticating MongoCredential{mechanism=SCRAM-SHA-1, userName='dashboarduser', source='dashboarddb', password=" 
* If I run the collector with the db user/pwd commented out in application.properties, it runs (no repo data is pulled yet but it's hitting GitHub - I can solve that part)
* I also commented out the db user/pwd in dashboard.properties for consistency, but now the login screen is missing the form.  

A bit later today (I'm at work) I may just trying deleting and creating the database in case I've gotten something in a bad state somehow.  I would like to understand the user/pwd issue.   freecellwiz

443246191 Yes, thanks.  If I have other questions I'll use Gitter when I'm outside a corporate network. freecellwiz

# Database Password - default is blank
dbpassword=dbpassword

# Logging File location
logging.file=./logs/jira.log

# PageSize - Expand contract this value depending on Jira implementation's
# default server timeout setting (You will likely receive a SocketTimeoutException)
feature.pageSize=2000

# Delta change date that modulates the collector item task
# Occasionally, these values should be modified if database size is a concern
feature.deltaStartDate=2018-03-01T00:00:00.000000
feature.masterStartDate=2018-03-01T00:00:00.000000
feature.deltaCollectorItemStartDate=2018-03-01T00:00:00.000000

#PageSize
feature.pageSize=50


# Chron schedule: S M D M Y [Day of the Week]
feature.cron=0 * * * * *

# ST Query File Details - Required, but DO NOT MODIFY
feature.queryFolder=jiraapi-queries
feature.storyQuery=story
feature.epicQuery=epic
feature.projectQuery=projectinfo
feature.memberQuery=memberinfo
feature.sprintQuery=sprintinfo
feature.teamQuery=teaminfo
feature.trendingQuery=trendinginfo


######################

# JIRA CONNECTION DETAILS:
# Enterprise Proxy - ONLY INCLUDE IF YOU HAVE A PROXY
#feature.jiraProxyUrl=http://proxy.com
#feature.jiraProxyPort=9000
feature.jiraBaseUrl=https://jira.trimble.tools/
feature.jiraQueryEndpoint=rest/api/2/
# For basic authentication, requires username:password as string in base64
# This command will make this for you:  echo -n username:password | base64

feature.jiraCredentials=XXX

# OAuth is not fully implemented; please blank-out the OAuth values:

#feature.jiraOauthAuthtoken=
#feature.jiraOauthRefreshtoken=
#               feature.jiraOauthRedirecturi=
#               feature.jiraOauthExpiretime=

#############################################################################
# In Jira, general IssueType IDs are associated to various 'issue'
# attributes. However, there is one attribute which this collector's
# queries rely on that change between different instantiations of Jira.
# Please provide a string name reference to your instance's IssueType for
# the lowest level of Issues (for example, 'user story') specific to your Jira
# instance.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's IssueType Name
# listings via the following URI:  https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issuetype/
# Multiple comma-separated values can be specified.
#############################################################################
feature.jiraIssueTypeNames=Story

#############################################################################
# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for 'sprint' or 'timebox' details,
# which includes a list of information.  This field allows you to specify that data field for your
# instance of Jira. Note: You can retrieve your instance's sprint data field name
# via the following URI, and look for a package name com.atlassian.greenhopper.service.sprint.Sprint;
# your custom field name describes the values in this field:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
#############################################################################
#feature.jiraSprintDataFieldName=customfield_10000
feature.jiraSprintDataFieldName=customfield_10105

#############################################################################
# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for 'super story' or 'epic' back-end ID,
# which includes a list of information.  This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance
# of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's epic ID field name via the following URI where your
# queried user story issue has a super issue (for example, epic) tied to it; your custom field name describes the
# epic value you expect to see, and is the only field that does this for a given issue:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
#############################################################################
#feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName=customfield_10002
feature.jiraEpicIdFieldName=customfield_10107

#############################################################################
# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for 'story points'
# This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance
# of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's storypoints ID field name via the following URI where your
# queried user story issue has story points set on it; your custom field name describes the
# story points value you expect to see:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
#############################################################################
feature.jiraStoryPointsFieldName=customfield_10102
#feature.jiraStoryPointsFieldName=customfield_10003

#############################################################################
# In Jira, your instance will have its own custom field created for 'team'
# This field allows you to specify that data field for your instance
# of Jira.  Note:  You can retrieve your instance's team ID field name via the following URI where your
# queried user story issue has team set on it; your custom field name describes the
# team value you expect to see:
# https://[your-jira-domain-name]/rest/api/2/issue/[some-issue-name]
#############################################################################
feature.jiraTeamFieldName=

# Set this to true if you use boards as team
feature.jiraBoardAsTeam=false

logging.level.com.capitalone.dashboard.collector=DEBUG
logging.level.com.capitalone.dashboard=DEBUG
logging.level.com.atlassian.jira=DEBUG

#Core Artifacts
# These arrays of status mappings must be completed in order for custom source system statuses to be providable by
# Hygieia.  Currently, Hygieia only maps to the following 3 status mappings:  to do, doing, and done.  You can find
# all available issue status mappings by going to your instance's version of the following API call:
# http://fake.jira.com/rest/api/2/status/.  Your statuses are listed in the JSON response as "name."
feature.todoStatuses[0]=
feature.doingStatuses[0]=
feature.doneStatuses[0]=

column2: The collector queried Gitlab with its current time, and then just added a 'Z' behind it.  It was inaccurate since the local time to the collector has not to be necessarily GMT.  Fixed in order to query a precise date and time.

column2: This changes the behavior for merges to master. Currently builds are failing because the build triggered by merges to master attempt to deploy snapshots, but if the version in the pom is not a SNAPSHOT then it'll try to deploy a release and will fail due to insufficient permissions to overwrite an existing version. Now, on merge to master no deploy will be attempted.

column2:
The Bamboo collector inline [documentation](https://hygieia.github.io/Hygieia/bamboo.html)  of the properties file indicates that we should be using an API key. The erroneous snippet is shown below

```
# If using username/token for API authentication
# (required for Cloudbees Jenkins Ops Center) see sample
bamboo.servers[1]=http://username:token@bamboo.company.com

# Another option: If using same username/password Jenkins auth,
# set username/apiKey to use HTTP Basic Auth (blank=no auth)
bamboo.username=
bamboo.apiKey=
```

The only API key which we use in this context is the Hygieia API key set in the api.properties file, but in reality you have to pass the password of the user and not the API key. This is extremely misleading and I wasted a lot of time on this and figured out only after looking at the source code. Can this be fixed? @mspiegel @jdamick @davidroman @cgorshing @jaredsmith
column5: Misleading Documentation

column2:
Looking through the code, it appears that the `Dockerfile`s in the various directories do not actually *build* the binaries.  Rather, they expect them to already exist and add them into the image.

I'm working on adding OAuth2 support to the jenkins collector, and I'm trying to build the collector image so I can deploy it to openshift.  I had to hack the collector's `pom.xml` a lot to get it to build, as it depends on the top-level `pom.xml`.  I also edited the collector's `Dockerfile` to do a `mvn install`.  

Hoping to not butcher the `pom.xml` too much, I tried just running the image from the top level `Hygieia` directory, passing in the path to the `Dockerfile` I wanted.  When trying to use the maven structure as-is, running `docker build -f collector/build/jenkins/docker/Dockerfile`, I get messages about the `maven-surefire` plugin crashing, though it appears that it is only defined in the `UI-Tests` module.  

Admittedly, I do not have a lot of maven experience, I mostly use and and gradle, and I'm sure that there are good  reasons for the hierarchical project structure.  I'm wondering if there are any plans to:

+ Have the `Dockerfiles` actually build the binaries they expect to see in `dist`, `target`, etc.
+ As a consequence of this, it will probably be necessary to make the maven projects more independent of each other
column5: Dockerfiles do not build the code
column11:
436843866 I did a little more reading, and found out that the `-pl` option exists in Maven, so I can use that to just build one module.  

Re: the builder images, this might be just a specific use case, but I still think there would be value in creating them for e.g. containerized CI systems, developer onboarding, openshift imagestreams and buildconfigs, etc. tomgeorge
444721522 We are working on separating things okay. We have started with the core module. This issue will be resolved once we have finished that migration. I’m going to go ahead and close this.  Sbrenthughes

In the url https://username:APIKEY@mybamboo.company.com userName is the bamboo user name and APIKEY is the one which is set in api.properties. 

Following is the application.properties for the bamboo collector

                # Database Name
		dbname=dashboarddb

		# Database HostName - default is localhost
		dbhost=localhost

		# Database Port - default is 27017
		dbport=27017

		# MongoDB replicaset
		# [false if you are not using MongoDB replicaset]
		dbreplicaset= false

		# Database Username - default is blank
		dbusername=test

		# Database Password - default is blank
		dbpassword=test

		# Collector schedule (required)
		bamboo.cron=0 0/1 * * * *

		# Jenkins server (required) - Can provide multiple
		bamboo.servers[0]=https://username:APIKEY@mybamboo.company.com

		# If using username/token for API authentication
		# (required for Cloudbees Jenkins Ops Center) see sample
		#bamboo.servers[1]=https://username:APIKEY@mybamboo.company.com

		# Determines if build console log is collected - defaults to false
		# (Bamboo for some reason has not exposed it as an API)
		bamboo.saveLog=false

Can you please help out in identifying what is being done wrong here? If you need any additional information, do let me know
column5: Client exception loading jobs
column11:
435592094 The APIKEY used is the one in the API.properties. Is that the right one to use? kjaeswar76
436387307 The APIKEY you are referring to is the one that you would get from Bamboo to Access it's APIs. The key in the API properties is for use in Hygieia.  Sbrenthughes
436610705 Thanks @Sbrenthughes . In my case, it started working when I gave the password of the user instead of the API key from the API properties file.

Also I set the 
bamboo.username=<userName>
bamboo.apiKey=<Password>

and made this entry
# Jenkins server (required) - Can provide multiple
bamboo.servers[0]=https://username:APIKEY@mybamboo.company.com

as 

# Jenkins server (required) - Can provide multiple
bamboo.servers[0]=https://mybamboo.company.com

It started working like a charm after that.. kjaeswar76

column2:
We can now display Performance Tests on the UI. 
Users can click them and a popup with display with more details about the test results. The Popup includes a link to the origin of test results. When the test name is too long we now display a tooltip when hover.

 
![perftestview](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/26173728/47860403-d31daa80-ddc6-11e8-8deb-d61566658e2b.png)
column5: PR for displaying Performance test on the UI

column2:
- Publisher now prints the version of plugin on the jenkins build console.
- Publisher also prints link to Hygieia Dashboard on the jenkins build console if a dashboard is associated for the build.
- Created a new rest api endpoint "/v3/build" which returns an Object instead of the String as in previous versions.
- Implemented feature to publish to multiple endpoints from Jenkins Global Configuration and fixed the issue with Test Connection button for multiple endpoints.
- Added Tooltips for the new fields to support the above mentioned functionalities.
column5: Hygieia Jenkins Plugin Enhancements - v2.1.6

Hi guys,
I am working on Udeploy collector. 
I'm using a Docker file to run Udeploy collector and. also import ssl certificate.


FROM openjdk:8-jre

VOLUME ["/hygieia/logs"]

RUN mkdir /hygieia/config

EXPOSE 8080

ENV PROP_FILE /hygieia/config/application.properties

COPY certificates/ /usr/local/share/ca-certificates/
RUN update-ca-certificates && \
    ls -1 /usr/local/share/ca-certificates | while read cert; do \
        openssl x509 -outform der -in /usr/local/share/ca-certificates/$cert -out $cert.der; \
        keytool -import -alias $cert -keystore $JAVA_HOME/lib/security/cacerts -trustcacerts -file $cert.der -storepass changeit -noprompt; \
        rm $cert.der; \
    done

WORKDIR /hygieia

COPY target/*.jar /hygieia
COPY docker/properties-builder.sh /hygieia/

CMD ./properties-builder.sh &&\
  java -Djava.security.egd=file:/dev/./urandom -jar *.jar --spring.config.location=$PROP_FILE


------------------------------------

433918547 @ashu16815 Adding new dashboard to Hygieia project requires these components,

1. Collector
2. UI widget
3. REST Endpoints to query aggregated data

**Hygieia Collector** is a Spring Boot process designed to collect & aggregate DevOps data and persist it to datastore(Default - MongoDB). You can take a look at [SCM collector](https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/tree/master/collectors/scm/github) to understand how a collector is implemented. 

**UI Widgets** are maintained [here]( https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/tree/master/UI/src/components/widgets). You can follow these widgets and create similar code for new widget. For example you can copy repo folder and rename to "AZURE_BUILD_WIDGET". Each widget in Hygieia is uniquely identified by its name. During widget creation widget name is passed in the REST API call and that way REST API can resolve its name by mapping it to a predertmined itentifier. An example [widget name](https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/blob/master/UI/src/components/widgets/repo/config.js#L215) which is mapped to Collector type SCM [here]( https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/blob/master/api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/service/DashboardServiceImpl.java#L590).

**REST Endpoints** are created as Spring Controller, please see [GitRequestController](https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/blob/master/api/src/main/java/com/capitalone/dashboard/rest/GitRequestController.java). You need to supply ComponentID and some more parameter unique to your widget. 

Other than above, you can find plethora of information on Hygieia by following its [online documentation](https://hygieia.github.io/Hygieia/getting_started.html).

Related : https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/issues/2518

cc: @tabladrum  shishirchaturvedi

column2:
As part of the Hygieia planning session at Verizon this past summer, SingleStone committed to working on a few new features. This one relates to simplifying the initial setup of Hygieia.
 
**Problem:** 
The initial installation and configuration of Hygieia is time consuming and requires many steps and tools to be installed (e.g. Java, Maven, Node, gulp, Mongo, etc.). From personal experience this can take 1-3 hours depending on the installers familiarity with all the tools listed above. Based on a discussion with @tabladrum, this is one of the largest sources of issues from the Hygieia community and solving this issue would result in less support issues being generated.
 
**Outcomes:** 
A new user can get Hygieia up and running in less than 10 minutes (from initial download to dashboard created and being populated with real data).
 
**Design Thoughts:**
1. Reasonable defaults should be used so streamlined installation can support ~100 teams or dashboards out of the box with minimal/no configuration. More sophisticated highly available and fault-tolerant installations are beyond the initial scope.
1. When Hygieia is “run” this means the UI, API and the default set of collectors required to populate the default dashboard are automatically started from a single command. 
1. Ideally the user can configure which collectors are started in a simple way and/or the can shutoff previously started collectors quickly.
1. The approach should be cloud-native, but support on premise / local installations too.

**Design Options:**
**Docker Hub** - A publicly available image containing all the software necessary to run Hygieia pre-installed. Users would install with “docker pull hygieia” and run with “docker run hygieia”. This image would include all the current “capitalone/hygieia-*” repos currently published on [hub.docker.com](hub.docker.com) (basically the UI, API and reasonable default set of collectors in a single image).

**AWS ECS & EKS** - Similar to above, this would enable a user with an AWS account to launch Hygieia in a managed environment. To launch, the user would choose the Hygieia image, create a task definition, configure the service and cluster before launching. 

**Hygieia AMI** - A baked AMI published to the AWS Marketplace with all Hygieia components installed that is used to stand-up a new instance. Once a user logs into their AWS account, from the marketplace, they specify the Action Type, EC2 instance size, VPC, Subnet, Security Group and Key Pair then clicks Launch to start the server.

**Next Steps**
This issues is meant to start a discussion in this community on how to proceed forward. Before writing code, we want to tease out other requirements, ideas and options on how this might be done before implementing it (likely starting in December).
column5: Streamline Hygieia Onboarding
column11:
434759557 Love the Installation Generator idea. The generator itself can generate the properties file for the collectors or even register hooks (such as github webhook). This may be interesting https://github.com/codecentric/spring-boot-admin/issues/99  tabladrum
434792704 I like the Installation Generator idea too. I think one of the primary advantages to an approach like that would be the ability to vet the inputs that the user provides, alerting them when there are issues with the information provided. Although this approach would be somewhat limited in it's ability to scale as you need to follow the GHE appliance model where all layers exist on the same instance, image, etc, but I think it would be very good for small to medium sized consumers.  matthewbeasley
434913831 So along the Installation Generator idea, I think we should focus on a few main threads, perhaps in parallel:

First, we should figure out how to ask natural questions about how the user wants Hygieia to help them and capture their answers in a meaningful format for use later. I'm happy to help here but would like to pair with @tabladrum or some others to flush this out a bit. Might pull in Kevin Tuskey here too.

Second, we should figure out how to translate their answers into Hygieia configuration without requiring major changes to Hygieia itself. Perhaps @jayhogan can help here with assistance from others.

Third, we should figure out how this generator will be deployed and operated. Open to anyone who wants to help on this one.

For the first one, I'm envisioning a web survey/intuitive guide that prompts the user to answer certain questions about what they want Hygieia to help them manage (team, product, portfolio, pipelines, etc.) and uses their answers plus some code/automation to output 1) exact instructions/configurations for the user to make on external systems and 2) configuration file(s) that Hygieia can consume to make it work like the user expects it should work based on their answers. 

Open to feedback on any of this.
 ryanshriver
435093915 For the second and third threads I imagined something like a single docker image (could also be AMI) that contains the bare essentials, DB, api, UI and maybe audit-api. The first time the user goes to the UI in their browser they are redirected to a wizard which goes through the setup process asking the questions from your first thread. Based on the answers provided the generator would create properties files like we use today, download the appropriate collectors and start them using the generated properties files for configuration. Then it would use the remote dashboard api to create the corresponding dashboards. Finally it would set a flag denoting the installation is complete and subsequent visits to the UI would behave as usual. This could be built directly into the UI making it so that we don't have to do anything additional to deploy the generator.  matthewbeasley
465277527 After identifying and debating a few design options we’ve decided to go in this direction to implement an MVP that simplifies the initial setup of Hygieia. Target date is late March / early April to:

1. Automate the setup of a Hygieia environment in AWS using CloudFormation
2. Deploy Hygieia as a set of containers running on ECS (one each for UI, API and each collector)
3. Fetch Hygieia containers at deployment time from public Dockyard repo
4. User configuration choices including what collectors to run are passed as CloudFormation parameters at setup time

Notes:

1. At some point a GUI-based way for the user to select/configure the collectors is possible and we'd like to do it, but it would be hard to do with the current Hygieia architecture. Our proposed MVP solution doesn’t preclude this at some point later, but for MVP we decided against a GUI for now.

2. The solution is Docker-based so should be relatively portable, but for simplicity we chose to deploy this on AWS initially. We leverage the AWS ECS Fargate service for hosting the containers and the DocumentDB service for hosting the MongoDB so there are no virtual servers to maintain with the solution.

3. Based on internal testing, it takes about 12 minutes to provision and configure all AWS resources to run Hygieia. At that point the Admin can start building dashboards. This is very close to our 10 minute original goal (above) and perhaps as we implement we can streamline this slightly to get to under 10 minutes.

4. We make reasonable defaults to “wire together” the different Hygieia services without user’s having to specify every configuration. However, these can be overridden via CloudFormation parameters.


We’re in the process of implementing this solution and will create a PR with all proposed changes when done, ideally by late March / early April. More to come, feedback welcome. ryanshriver
434713371 I would say these are reasonable goals and options but the devil will be in the details. Honestly, I don’t think the deployment approach is the challenge and so any of the options mentioned above will likely work. To me, the challenge will be making the configuration of the individual components simple and easy. For example, each collector needs to be configured to point to the instance of whatever tool is being used (i.e. Jenkins, GitHub, etc..). In some cases, the external tool itself will need to be configured. For instance, it is better to use Github webhooks and the Jenkins Hygieia plugin than rely on the batch collection strategy. This feels like a huge barrier to getting started, especially if the person does not have administrative access to the tools or just doesn’t know the details to get the dashboard up and running.

I think we should take to heart the feedback provided in #2540. I'm sure the documentation is accurate and provides all of the relevant details needed to standup a Hygieia instance with any required collectors. However, can a person new to Hygieia consume all of this documentation and get a working version of Hygieia running in 10 minutes or less?

Here are some potential enhancements to @ryanshriver's proposal that could solve these challenges:

1. **Hygieia Installation Generator** - What if we created a web-based generator or CLI that guided a user through the installation and configuration process. The output would be a scaffolded installation that takes advantage of 1 or more of the design options mentioned above, with the configuration files populated based on the user's answers.
1. **Unified properties file** - I know it is not recommended to merge config files but this is a reasonable approach to reduce "getting started" overhead. We could provide a sample config file with as many reasonable defaults as possible and provide clear guidance in a getting started document. Hopefully we could limit the user changes to a single config file.

Thoughts? jayhogan
434759557 Love the Installation Generator idea. The generator itself can generate the properties file for the collectors or even register hooks (such as github webhook). This may be interesting https://github.com/codecentric/spring-boot-admin/issues/99  tabladrum
434792704 I like the Installation Generator idea too. I think one of the primary advantages to an approach like that would be the ability to vet the inputs that the user provides, alerting them when there are issues with the information provided. Although this approach would be somewhat limited in it's ability to scale as you need to follow the GHE appliance model where all layers exist on the same instance, image, etc, but I think it would be very good for small to medium sized consumers.  matthewbeasley

column2:
PR for issue TEART-21795

When a field is changed to empty in the quality widget it was not able to be saved, as the associateCollectorToComponent function only updates based off of new values being passed, not values omitted. This fix checks to see if other values from the quality widget are being updated so that if a value is missing, it can be assumed that the previous value (if there was any) was deleted.

**Caveat: this will not work if all values from the widget are deleted from the configure page as there is no way to determine the widget type is there are no collector types in the request. We would need to keep track of this relationship in order to fix this functionality. As an alternative, the delete button will delete the entire widget and all values, resulting in the same effect.

Adding a build/run strategy more familiar to many UI/UX devs.

To build:
```
cd UI
npm install
npm run build
```

To run:
```
cd UI
npm install
npm start
```

This needs some work on the `bower` side before its complete...

I guess I should also ask... since `bower` appears to be nearing a sunset, is there any interest in migrating the bower components to *webpack* or *yarn*?

column2:
PR for issue TEART-21795

When a field is changed to empty in the quality widget it was not able to be saved, as the associateCollectorToComponent function only updates based off of new values being passed, not values omitted. This fix checks to see if other values from the quality widget are being updated so that if a value is missing, it can be assumed that the previous value (if there was any) was deleted. 

**Caveat: this will not work if _all_ values from the widget are deleted from the configure page as there is no way to determine the widget type is there are no collector types in the request. We would need to keep track of this relationship in order to fix this functionality. As an alternative, the delete button will delete the entire widget and all values, resulting in the same effect.

Hi guys,

I'm wondering if it's possible publish more than one app per time with this plugin.
I know that I can use a pattern name (*.jar, *.war, *.java, ...) in the Artifact Name field, however I've not figured out any way to attribute different versions to them.

For example, let's assume that I have 2 files, core.jar and core-extension.jar. The first file version is 1.0.0 and the second one version is 2.0.1. I can set the Artifact Name to *.jar to deploy both files at once. However, Hygieia shows up that both .jar files versions are 1.0.0.

Is it possible set 1.0.0 to core.jar and 2.0.1 to core-extension.jar running the plugin only once?

Hey,

I'm new to Hygieia and am trying to get Hygieia up and running and connect to our Github Enterprise using Docker Compose by following [the official documentation](http://hygieia.github.io/Hygieia/builddocker.html).  But have run into a few issues.

Step 1 & 2 went fine.

Step 3 I start having issues, firstly there's no container named `mongodb2`, but I figure they mean `hygieia_db_1`, so I exec into that instead with

```
docker exec -it hygieia_db_1 bash
```
However, when I try to execute the command it errors out saying it cannot connect to `192.168.64.2/admin`.  I figure since this _is_ the mongo container I can just use localhost, which instead gives me the error `User "dashboarduser@dashboarddb" already exists`.  Well, seems like this is done, cool?

Stop 4 brings up more problems.  Since, the example configuration in the documentation doesn't line up with the services in `docker-compose.yml` or `docker-compose.override.example.yml`, I assume it's outdated and instead go with the `override.example.yml` in the repo, but change the `github-collector:` as follows:

```yaml
  github-collector:
    environment:
    - GITHUB_HOST=<our enterprise ip>
    - GITHUB_CRON=0 * * * * *
    - GITHUB_COMMIT_THRESHOLD_DAYS=300
```

For Step 5 the restart seems to work.  The `docker port` command once again doesn't work because there's no container named `hygieia-ui` so I opt for the `hygieia_ui_1`.  And use that port to login via my browser.

I create a user then try to create an example dashboard with a `repo` widget to verify the github integration works.  But there's no option in the "Select a type" drop down.

![select-a-type](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/25732263/47313944-462c6180-d60e-11e8-9ef8-e1f62b3e9f1f.png)

What did I do wrong?  Is there more complete documentation for the docker-compose somewhere?

435096611 @AaronNBrock : Apologies, couldn't respond to you until now. Firstly, thanks for the step-by-step details that you provided. Yes, the documentation might need slight changes. 

But, to answer your question, the reason you are not seeing any options in the drop down menu on the UI is because the github collector has not run properly and registered in the database. 
 I looked at the Dockerfile and the "properties-builder.sh" files for the gihub-scm-collector (collectors/scm/github), and it might be that you are missing the following properties in your "docker-compose-override.yml". 

Can you please add these to your properties list under "environment", and try again?

1. **MONGODB_HOST**: Set it to "localhost" or the IP of the machine you are running the database on
2. **GITHUB_KEY**: 
This is the key value used to encrypt the user-id/password details or the personal access token of the private repos that you would register on the Code Repo Widget on Hygieia.
You will have to logon to the UI with an admin account to be able to generate this token.
Please check in the mongodb "user_info" collection  to see if there is an "admin" account available.
If not, I think you'll have to create one: Example of an admin account below:

{
    "username" : "<admin user id>", 
    "authorities" : [
        "ROLE_USER", 
        "**ROLE_ADMIN**"
    ], 
    "authType" : "STANDARD", 
    "firstName" : "", 
    "middleName" : "", 
    "lastName" : "", 
    "displayName" : "", 
    "emailAddress" : ""
}

3. **PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN**:
This access token key value would be used to connect to the github repo you register on the ui, if you haven't provided any user-id/password or access token on the widget. In which case, it would have to be a public repo accessible via this token that you provide.

Hope this helps, thanks battinasubodh

Changes to all dashboards to be updated based on the provided Business Service and Business Application and not just the title. 

With old logic if a Dashboard exist with a Business Service and Business Application but was being updated via the API and the Titles didn't match, the update would fail. Dashboards with a Business Service and Business Application combination are unique so the dashboard should be updated, if they match, no matter what the title is.

430186918 Hi, As I can understand you are trying to fetch Build status of a job from Jenkins to Hygieia.
In order to integrate Hygieia with Jenkins you need to do some configurations.

http://hygieia.github.io/Hygieia/hygieia-jenkins-plugin.html

**Jenkins side**
1. Upload .hpi file from your "Hygieia\hygieia-jenkins-plugin" folder to Jenkins plugin section then you will be able to see the Hygieia Publisher in Job's Post Build action.
2. You need to set "Hygieia Server URL" in Global Hygieia Publisher Settings. For that Goto Manage Jenkins > configure system > Global Hygieia Publisher Settings

**Now in Hygieia side**
1. Set  application.properties ( I guess you already did) in your (\Hygieia\collectors\build\jenkins\target) folder.
2. Follow step from http://hygieia.github.io/Hygieia/jenkins.html to Run or Deploy Jenkins collector in separate cmd prompt.
Use cmd:
`java -jar [your-jenkins-build-collector].jar --spring.config.name=jenkins --spring.config.location=application.properties`

Make sure your MongoDB client and Hygieia API is running. To check if Hygieia API is running use http://localhost:8080/api/ping, it should return true in browser.

Hope it helps! yadurajshakti
431383398 @yadurajshakti - this is great information! Thank you for taking the time to help others. I do want to point out though that you don't need the jenkins plugin AND the jenkins collector. Both get you the same data so you just need to pick the one that suits you best. The jenkins plugin has better overall performance since it is push based as opposed to pull based like the collector. I would say the only time you should bother with the collector is if you are using a jenkins instance managed by someone else and you don't have the ability to install the plugin.  matthewbeasley
431593123 @matthewbeasley - Thank you so much!!! Now I have understood.

So yeah, We need to configure either **Jenkins side** (Push-based) OR **Hygieia side** (Pull-based) based on your need.

 yadurajshakti

column2: Topo,  Here are my deltas to four of the 2.0.4 data collectors that I had do make to get them to work reliably on our network.  They are:  gitlab, sonar, udeploy, jenkins.  There are two styles of code change.  From what I can see across both the 2.0.4 and 2.0.5 code, these two should take care of the whole issue.  Since the README.md files have moved, I just added some contextualized comments in each to show what these changes should look like in the new locations.  CAVEAT EMPTOR:  I have NOT compiled this code as my environment would take far longer to set up for this than to just enter the deltas into the 2.0.5 source base.  Furthermore, since you are just looking for methodology and will promote the logic to the base class anyway, I figure that what I have supplied will be sufficient for this part of the task.  Best regards,  Daniel Lydick

column2:
This PR:
- Modifies the Travis Build to:
    - `mvn clean install` only on PRs
    - Builds and deploys snapshot versions on merges to master (assuming the pom.xml specifies SNAPSHOT)
    - Builds and deploys release versions to oss.sonatype.org on tagged commits (assuming SNAPSHOT is not included in the pom.xml version tag)
- Increments all the versions of our modules to 3.0.0-SNAPSHOT

The intention for this PR is to perform final testing on this build by building and deploying the SNAPSHOTS. Afterward a follow-up PR should be submitted removing "SNAPSHOT" from the versions and a GitHub release should be created with a version matching the version in the poms.
column5: Overhaul Travis Builds

column2:
I added required environment properties for Jenkins collector to docker-compose.override.yml file but docker container dies after couple of seconds. 

I believe the issue is "--spring.config.location" in Dockerfile is pointing to a non existing file called  "application.properties"

I modified the "collectors/build/jenkins/docker/Dockerfile" to point the spring config to "hygieia-jenkins-build-collector.properties" and now container starts up without any issues. 

`"ENV PROP_FILE /hygieia/config/hygieia-jenkins-build-collector.properties"`
 
https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/blob/6ea1b067ffd1c59d4b280e2e455730c14dcb8f38/collectors/build/jenkins/docker/Dockerfile#L15
column5: hygieia_jenkins-build-collector docker container exits after couple of seconds
column11:
429912252 @sbabutk - if you'll notice the referenced line in the dockerfile is a `ENV` line. This means that if you add `-e PROP_FILE /path/to/expected/properties` it will override that variable without need for modifying the dockerfile. Ideally though you should be using the jenkins plugin we provide as there are some performance issues for the jenkins build collectors on jenkins instances with a large number of jobs.  matthewbeasley
432668694 Thank you, Jenkins plugin is working fine.

I was following the "https://hygieia.github.io/Hygieia/builddocker.html" to build and run docker image using maven and it failed so I still think it is a defect. (default config location is pointing to a test properties file instead of hygieia-jenkins-build-collector.properties) sbabutk
455353088 Agree with @sbabutk. Following the instructions on this site regarding creating and running the Docker Containers using docker-compose doesn't actually work and won't work for ANY of the collectors as they ALL have the same pattern of using application.properties rather than the name of what the actual properties files should be. I think it's worth correcting. Should just be a matter of changing the shall script use application.properties or modifying the Dockerfile to suit the collector. 

Other alternative is to modify the instructions so that people aren't caught scratching their heads on why it isn't working and having to debug this every single time.  daniel-ng
455353353 Can you make a PR to the documentation? I think MatthewBeasley comment is pretty straight forward on how to override the properties.  Sbrenthughes
500447735 Hello, everyone!

I've been trying to follow the Hygieia documentation @ https://hygieia.github.io/Hygieia/setup.html for about a week before stumbling onto this page. I second that alternative of modifying the instructions. At the very least, a fix like the one here should be more visible to newcomers learning this on their own (as I am) so that they don't get discouraged.

Thank you all for offering solutions to this problem! JFDonaghy

column2:
Per the docs for SonarQube at https://docs.sonarqube.org/display/DEV/Web+API when using token based authentication then the token goes into the username part, followed by a colon and empty password.

The current code base does not allow a null password, it is expecting both a username and password, this PR corrects that.

See https://docs.sonarqube.org/display/DEV/Web+API
column5: Allow tokens to be used for SonarQube authentication

column2:
Hi, 

I am trying to implement multiple same type widgets on a single dashboard. For example, having multiple GitLab repositories or multiple Jenkins builds in the same dashboard. 

Looking at the MongoDB and Java classes, I can see that each dashboard contains an application,  which contains an array of components.  A component then contains a map of CollectorType:ListOfCollectorItem, meaning that in theory, it can contain multiple Gitlab repos or Jenkins builds. Now it looks as if the current implementation should in theory allow multiple same type widgets, but that is not the case. I can see two ways of doing this. For example, let's say we want two GitLab repositories on the same dashboard: 

1) A dashboard contains an application, and this application contains two components. 
      Component A: has GitLab repo 1
      Component B: has GitLab repo 2
2) A dashboard contains an application, the application contains one component.
     Component A: has two GitLab repos 

Since I can't really wrap my head around this, could you explain why currently multiple same type widgets are not supported, and what is the limitation? Just FYI, I am not a front-end guy, so I haven't investigated the UI that much, maybe the limitation is on that side?

Thanks
column5: Multiple same type widgets on the same dashboard - what is the limitation?
column11:
431581064 @stevegal I made the first changes regarding the delete operation on a widget. You can see the changes here: https://github.com/dardanbekteshi/Hygieia/commit/ea31677c760ee2ed8904aeabe98e8006adaca3c2

I created a branch feature/multiple_widgets which is up to date with the original Hygieia master. I think that is the easiest way to collaborate. Please have a look at the change, maybe checkout the branch and add further changes. 

As it is now, the create and update operations will not work, and the problem I see is in the disable/enable field of a given collector item. Since when we update a given widget, that will mean that we need to disable the previous collector item which was "holding its place" in the component. And the reason for this is that whenever a widget is updated, a new collector item is created in the database, instead of updating the original one. IMO, this makes things more complicated, since as it is right now, we don't have a way to trace back and check which exact collector item is the old one. Because currently only one widget of a given type was supported, this was easy, and we could delete or disable all the collector items of a given type.

My guess is that there has to be a way to send some more information from the frontend to the back, like for example, send all the collector items of the component in a separate parameter, and then send the collector item we are interested in on a separate parameter. Right now, it looks like we are sending a List<CollectorItemId>, but from what I have seen, it is always only one collectoritemid (i.e. a singleton List).

But maybe we can further discuss once you have a look at the changes, and we can directly highlight snippets of code we think needs to be changed, might be easier :) 

And also, you can share your UI changes on another branch maybe, so I can also have a look and try to merge backend/frontend changes. dardanbekteshi
432981139 FYI, if anyone wants to contribute to this feature being developed ASAP you can join me and @stevegal on the following branch: https://github.com/dardanbekteshi/Hygieia/tree/feature/multiple_widgets

ping @HweeWong, @divashdr

New commits, comments, observations are more than welcomed (especially frontend - Angular)!  dardanbekteshi

434864856 We’ve got multiple widgets configurable on new dashboards, working for build widgets, feature widgets, repo widgets (WIP), code widgets (WIP), performance widgets (WIP), rally widgets (WIP). Looking promising so far. Should I raise a PR before completion for early feedback? stevegal
434865350 @stevegal I'd say yes, go ahead! dardanbekteshi
428538289 An answer I got on Gitter from @nireeshT, just in case someone else is interested into this question: 

> "your 2nd option is feasible way for implementing multiple same type widget. Consider widget as collector_item in component. Component is dashboard" dardanbekteshi
429916270 Hi @dardanbekteshi, I am looking for a solution for this as well. Do you think there is any backend code changes required? Or is it just UI changes?  HweeWong
429942621 Hi @HweeWong, I am not entirely sure, and that's why I raised this issue. But from what I have seen, changes are required in both backend and frontend.

I just read (#2495) that you have already done some UI changes, while I have done some research on the backend side. I have created the following diagram which consists of the mongoDB and Java code mapping.
 
![backend-diagram](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/23189173/46967014-92781e80-d0af-11e8-9849-5023bb8e29fa.png)

From what I see, the dashboard's Widget is connected to the component's CollectorItem. So, when someone deletes a widget, the backend needs to synchronize between these two classes, making sure that both the Dashboard and Component classes (and therefore the MongoDB collections) are updated. IMO, that's why the two repo widgets that you have created appear to be linked as they might point to the same CollectorItem! I am still not 100% sure, and I hope to have clarified this on Friday.

I think that we should join forces regarding this feature, where I can focus on the backend and you on the frontend? If you agree, then I suggest that you create a branch (e.g. multiple-widgets) and push the UI related code. I'll then have a look at it on Friday and start to make the backend changes accordingly. At the moment, I only work once a week on Hygieia since I am also involved in another project, but I think we can still have progress if we collaborate :)   dardanbekteshi
430034413 Doesn’t the config for a widget contain an array of collector items? The collector items are gathered at the backend and only linked through the widget config to the collector item... at least that’s what I thought when I recently did the log widget. And I too would appreciate multiple widgets! stevegal
430398453 From what I can see from looking at the `widgetConfigManager.js` and `widgetConfigManager.html` it adds/removes widgets based on widgetTitle. I reckon if you could change that and just expose an addWidget and removeWidget that checks for all widgets that start with the title and simply adds with a new title then it may work. Just not sure if the widget type is based on the title.. If so that'd have to change as well. stevegal
430406582 btw.. think this is the same as #2468 

Anyway... further investigations... I can get multiple widgets to add on the config screen quite easily, but as feared the dashboard view tries to create i think based on the title. But I can't see why this.. with a bit of tweaking.. wouldn't work. Maybe @matthewbeasley or @rvema have views? stevegal
431251296 Would love to have this feature available to us as soon as earliest. Thanks! divashdr
431289189 @dardanbekteshi For the extra widget, I have just duplicated the repo widget under UI components to see how it works - ideally we wouldn't want to do this manually.. I am not a frontend person as well. Thanks for posting the diagram, it does make it much clearer for me to understand what is going on.

Am I right saying that the widget is linked to a dashboard and application, hence not allowing us to show multiple widget?  (componentId : modalData.dashboard.application.components[0].id) HweeWong
431455606 Thanks, @dardanbekteshi for re-opening this issue!.  divashdr
431458457 it would seem that the widget.js also assumes the name is the type... I'm pretty certain if we took the type of widget through and removes the assumptions that that widget title and the name were the same it would work. stevegal
431465617 @divashdr it was not intentional, I closed it by mistake :) 

@stevegal I spent the day investigating the backend and all the methods that do the create/update/delete operations on both the Dashboard and Component classes (and the corresponding MongoDB collections). I think I found the problem, and it mostly lies in the DashboardServiceImpl class. In particular, the methods deleteWidget() and associateCollectorToComponent(). 
But now it is too late, so I will finish with the changes tomorrow morning and will share the code and my observations with you. Then hopefully the needed UI changes will be more clear for you to proceed with.

I am looking forward to collaborating and solving the issue together :D  dardanbekteshi

or maybe the delete just needs to be a bit more clever... collect the collectorids to remove... instead of the types... stevegal

column11: 428977853 @shardulsrivastava: If you don't have any other questions at this time until later, I would like to go ahead and close this issue. Please let us know. Thanks ! subodhbattina 429020044 @Sbrenthughes the data m getting on the product dashboard for the environments, is not right, coz our builds automatically promote the code to the dev environments and then wait for the user input before promoting them further . hence data in COMMIT,BUILD,DEV should be in mins. Any idea where can i look in the code for the issue. As i can see that these details are being calculated from the timestamps with respect to the stages these timestamps are being calculated for each commit after getting the deployable units for every environment of the component : getEnvironments -> deployService.getDeployStatus -> getDeployStatus() -> Deployable Units are added from environment_component and environment_status tables. Now assuming that there is only one deployment collector then there will be only one deployable unit for every environment of a component, that too will be the latest deployment i.e deployable unit. now is it correct to calculate the stage timestamps based on the latest deployment , rather than calculating it based on the deployments for that commit. shardulsrivastava 429363827 My depth of knowledge about the specifics of the time calculations is limited at best. I would assume that since the product dashboard is tracking commits as the come and go through the stages, it would be better to use the timestamps for the deployment of the commits. Sbrenthughes 429548111 @Sbrenthughes can you please point me to someone who has actually written this logic, i just want to know whats the reasoning behind calculating this way in backend. shardulsrivastava 430457437 Let me do some digging and I will followup Sbrenthughes 428624277 @shardulsrivastava: Please look at each of the files "*-data.js" under: "UI/src/components/widgets/product/". column2:
Per the docs for SonarQube at https://docs.sonarqube.org/display/DEV/Web+API when using token based authentication then the token goes into the username part, followed by a colon and empty password.

The current code base does not allow a null password, it is expecting both a username and password, this PR corrects that.

See https://docs.sonarqube.org/display/DEV/Web+API

column2:
# Overall concept
It is hard to create/configure and keep dashboard configurations up to date as more and more pipeline steps are added/removed/changed. This is a first attempt to auto-detect related events/pipeline steps etc to auto-complete dashboards, auto-update dashboards as things change. For now, this is intended to work with Jenkins pipeline, but can be extended to work with any pipeline. 

Given a dashboard configured with a code repository, as the corresponding Jenkins pipeline is executed, with the enhanced Jenkins Hygieia plugin, the dashboard will automatically be updated with Build and Sonar widget (out of the box). Enhanced plugin has open configuration to allow other events (such as Open Source scan, security scan, tests etc) to be captured and allow the corresponding collectors to auto-configure the dashboards. 

# High Level Design
Event Listener classes now correlate between collector items and automatically adds related collector items to existing dashboards. A new collection "related_items" is used for this. Event listeners (or any other collector or api) can write pairs of collector items  that potentially are related to "related_items" collection. A new listener to this collection finds dashboards matching with either of these pairs and adds the other one (if not already there) to those dashboards. 

For example: Start with a dashboard with a repo configured. The component document for that dashboard will have 1 collector item (for the repo). Now, a new build building the repo is saved to builds collection. Build Event listener will save the build collector item and the repo collector item to "related_items" collection. Related Items event listener then will find the dashboard that was configured with the repo collector item and will add the build collector item. For sonar, the relation is drawn via build id saved in the code_quality collection. 
 
# Changes (High Level)
- New collections: related_items, generic_collector_items
- New listener: RelatedItemsEventListener
- Modified listeners: BuildEventListener and CodeQualityEventListener
- New Core Models and Repositories: RelatedItems, GenericCollectorItems
- New APIs: To CRUD to the new collections
- Enhanced Hygieia plugin for Jenkins: New Global configuration allows to send ALL build and Sonar results directly to Hygieia without having to configure any individual job. Option is also available to publish "raw" collector item data to Hygieia for the collectors that are running. 

![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6014941/46252158-e8539200-c432-11e8-87b7-2296dbfbb189.png)

Essentially it captures certain console log lines based on supplied regex for a given collector. Hygieia saves these "raw" data and the related build collector item id in a new collection "generic_collector_items". Corresponding collector can process/parse this raw data and find/create collector items as well save in the "related_items" collection. 

# More upcoming changes (Work in progress)
- All collectors will process the generic_collector_items collection and "pick up" its own set of data based on the collector name. 
- More standard tool integration in Jenkins plugin


@nireeshT @rvema @Satheesh-Balachandran @Sbrenthughes please review.

column11: 425907545 if you are using Jenkins for your build you can using the plugin to push the artifact data easily. Sbrenthughes 426326721 @Sbrenthughes i am not using jenkins but wrote a custom collector for cloud based CI called Buildkite. anyways i have modified the code to get it working. shardulsrivastava 426352320 @Sbrenthughes the data m getting on the product dashboard for the environments, is not right, coz our builds automatically promote the code to the dev environments and then wait for the user input before promoting them further . hence data in COMMIT,BUILD,DEV should be in mins. Any idea where can i look in the code for the issue. As i can see that these details are being calculated from the timestamps with respect to the stages these timestamps are being calculated for each commit after getting the deployable units for every environment of the component : getEnvironments -> deployService.getDeployStatus -> getDeployStatus() -> Deployable Units are added from environment_component and environment_status tables. Now assuming that there is only one deployment collector then there will be only one deployable unit for every environment of a component, that too will be the latest deployment i.e deployable unit. now is it correct to calculate the stage timestamps based on the latest deployment , rather than calculating it based on the deployments for that commit. shardulsrivastava 428407053 @shardulsrivastava I saw you above screenshot, PROD stage is the information I want, could you please tell me how to configure to get the information? My PROD stage information is similar as your DEV stage. yuhong02 495334415 closing the issue due to inactivity rvema

428234080 @marchenm: I think the question is, within your Dockerfile for the collector, how are you setting the properties that the collector expects. Ensure you are setting the KEY value on the properties file that the collector expects. 
Simple way of doing this would be to have your collector properties file with all the properties set, and then copy that properties file over in your Dockerfile for the image, and then start your container.
Example: 
```VOLUME /var/app/config
COPY ${JAR_FILE} /var/app/<collector jar file>
ENTRYPOINT ["java","-Djava.security.egd=file:/dev/./urandom","-jar","/var/app/collector jar file"]
CMD [ "--spring.config.location=/var/app/config/application.properties" ]```

"JAR_FILE" points to your collector jar in your compose file. subodhbattina

```dbname=<dbname>
dbreplicaset=false

github.cron=0 0/1 * * * *
github.host=github.com

# Maximum number of previous days from current date, when fetching commits

# Optional: Error threshold count after which collector stops collecting for a collector item. Default is 2.

428302429 After regenerating the apikey in the ui and adding it to the `docker-compose.override.yml` I was able to get encryption working by re-entering my github personal access token in the configuration ui. Why isn't it picking up the tocken from the properties file? 
https://github.com/Hygieia/Hygieia/blob/b9fd1dfc5bd823a14c925073ee5f38037b5e6d74/collectors/scm/github/docker/properties-builder.sh#L33 marchenm
428610274 @marchenm Firstly, just so i understand what you are saying: The "apiKey" and "personalAccessToken" are two different things:
1. "apiKey" is used purely for encryption and decryption
2. "personalAccessToken" is used for accessing the github api's.

That said: The docker compose file that you posted shows this below:
- KEY=tVT3AXZwufLmN/3+FfLNTLbmyMFK3+zW
- PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN= </github token/>

Where as "properties-builder.sh" shows this below:

```#This is the key generated using the Encryption class in core
github.key=${GITHUB_KEY}
#personal access token generated from github and used for making authentiated calls
github.personalAccessToken=${PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN}```

I hope you are reading the "apiKey" as "github.key=${KEY}".
Just wanted to point this out incase this is causing any failures .
This is right above where you set the "github.personalAccessToken" in the "properties-builder.sh".

That said:
Are you able to cat and share the properties file?
Also, could you please share your Dockerfile? Thanks. subodhbattina
428976164 @marchenm : Do you have any updates on this? thanks. subodhbattina
429176241 Right, I understand the difference. I set GITHUB_KEY is set to the apiKey that was generated in the ui.

After deploying the containers and generating the key in the ui I set it  in the `docker-compose.override.yml` as environment variables for the api container and the github collector. 
```
version: '3'
services:
  api:
    environment: # for a full list check the corresponding properties-builder file
      - SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_DATABASE={{ db_name }}
      - SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_HOST=db
      - SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PORT=27017
      - SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_USERNAME={{ db_user }}
      - SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PASSWORD={{ db_pass }}
      - KEY={{ github_apiKey }}
      - AUTH_SECRET={{ hygieia_auth_key }}
    volumes:
      - ./logs:/hygieia/logs

  github-collector:
    environment:
      - HYGIEIA_API_ENV_SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_USERNAME={{ db_user }}
      - HYGIEIA_API_ENV_SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_PASSWORD={{ db_pass }}
      - HYGIEIA_API_ENV_SPRING_DATA_MONGODB_DATABASE={{ db_name }}
      - MONGO_PORT=tcp://db:27017
      - MONGODB_HOST=db
      - MONGODB_PORT=27017
      - GITHUB_ERROR_THRESHOLD=25
      - GITHUB_KEY={{ hygieia_encrypt_key }}
      - GITHUB_HOST=https://github.com
      - GITHUB_CRON=0 * * * * *
      - GITHUB_COMMIT_THRESHOLD_DAYS=300
      - PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN={{ github_access_token }}
      - GITHUB_KEY={{ github_apiKey }}
```

Encryption now works; however, the github personal access token doesn't work when specified in the properties file. When I specify the github personal access token in the UI the collector pulls the github data.  marchenm
429356196 @marchenm 
When you specify the github personal access token in the UI, it gets stored in the database with the repo details, and collector is able to pull that out from the database.

Again, are you able to cat and see your properties file for the collector that the Dockerfile makes, can you please share that.
Just to debug, make the properties file at a location you are able to access it, before copying it into your image context folder, and then share the file please.
We want to make sure the property "github.personalAccessToken" is having the token value on the properties file.

The other thing is please share the logs or error you are seeing around the github access issues, it could be a proxy issue interfering with the request. Thanks. subodhbattina
431382175 @marchenm: If you dont have any updates on this, will go ahead and close the issue, thanks subodhbattina
432677936 @marchenm: Since I didn't see any updates, assuming this is resolved at your end. Closing the issue, thanks subodhbattina
435564772 @subodhbattina I don't thing that you understood @marchenm  issue/finding.

puting PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN in the properties files doesn't change anything, you have to do it fron the UI to get it to work. in this is due to : (DefaultGithubClient.java) 
`        String personalAccessToken = (String) repo.getOptions().get("personalAccessToken");
        String decryptedPersonalAccessToken = decryptString(personalAccessToken, settings.getKey());`
where repo is fetched from db pushed by API/UI, so the documentation is misleading and need to be updated.


 ysnoussi

column5: Unable to load projects and teams on versionone widget in hygieia dashboard
column11:
419550059 Issue fixed after using the correct token which is created with “Sys Admin” privileges in versionone.

1. Define an Access Token using the VersionOne UI: Go to Configuration - Applications and add a new Application with name Hygieia. 
Note: Person should have “Sys Admin” privileges to create the application.

2. After new application added, it will be listed under ‘select an application’ in Applications page, then generate public token to that application (In below page).
Navigation to open Applications page: Click on profile symbol at Top right corner  and select ‘Application’ and generate token. 

---
arun mulka.
